1 threatened with mistreatment or abuse or is neglected or dependent; or
2 (d) (i) no other state has jurisdiction under prerequisites substantially in accordance with
3 subsection (1)(a), (1)(b), or (1)(c) or another state has declined to exercise jurisdiction on the ground that this
4 state is the more appropriate forum to determine parenting of the child; and
5 (ii) it is in the child's best interest that the court assume jurisdiction.
6 (2) Except under subsections (1)(c) and (1)(d), physical presence in this state of the child or of the
7 child and one of the contestants is not alone sufficient to confer jurisdiction on a court of this state to make a
8 parenting determination.
9 (3) Physical presence of the child, while desirable, is not a prerequisite for jurisdiction to determine
10 parenting of the child.
11 (4) A parenting plan proceeding is commenced in the district court:
12 (a) by a parent, by filing a petition:
13 (i) for dissolution or legal separation;
14 (ii) for parenting in the county in which the child is permanently resident or found; or
15 (iii) for custody under 40-6-411; or
16 (b) by a person other than a parent if the person has established a child-parent relationship with
17 the child, by filing a petition for parenting in the county in which the child resides or is found.
18 (5) Notice of a parenting proceeding must be given to the child's parent, guardian, caretaker, those
19 persons with whom the child is physically residing, and all other contestants, who may appear, be heard, and
20 file a responsive pleading. The court, upon a showing of good cause, may permit intervention of other
21 interested parties.
22 (6) In a parenting plan proceeding under Title 40, chapter 4:
23 (a) orders issued by the district court must be timely filed in accordance with the facts and
24 circumstances of each individual case;
25 (b) orders involving stipulated matters must be granted as soon as reasonably practicable unless,
26 on review, the district court determines there is a need to modify or deny the stipulation; and
27 (c) following the submission of all evidence in a disputed matter or trial and, if requested, the
28 submission of any proposed order or proposed findings, the district court shall strive to issue a decision within
